  "prompt": "What do you do if you like someone?",
  "response": "Okay, so you like someone! That's exciting! Here's a breakdown of things you can do, broken down into categories, from subtle to more direct:\n\n**1. Self-Reflection and Preparation:**\n\n*   **Acknowledge Your Feelings:** First, be honest with yourself about how you feel.  Understanding the depth of your feelings helps you decide how to proceed.\n*   **Consider the Context:** What's your relationship with this person already? Are they a friend, a coworker, a classmate? What are the potential consequences of pursuing a romantic relationship in this context?\n*   **Manage Expectations:**  Not every crush leads to a relationship. Be prepared for different outcomes, including rejection. This will help you stay grounded and avoid getting too carried away.\n*   **Self-Care:** Continue to focus on your own happiness and well-being.  Don't put your life on hold while you're figuring out your feelings. Being confident and happy makes you more attractive, too!\n\n**2. Subtle Flirting & Building Connection:**\n\n*   **Spend Time Together:** Look for opportunities to casually hang out or work on projects together. This gives you more chances to get to know them and for them to get to know you.\n*   **Be Approachable & Positive:** Smile, make eye contact, and be generally friendly.  Positive energy is contagious!\n*   **Show Genuine Interest:** Ask them questions about their life, interests, and passions.  Listen attentively to their answers and show that you're engaged in the conversation.\n*   **Find Common Ground:**  Identify shared interests and activities.  This gives you something to talk about and a reason to spend time together.\n*   **Use Body Language:** Mirror their body language subtly (e.g., if they lean in, you lean in slightly).  Touch them casually and appropriately (e.g., a light touch on the arm when laughing). Be mindful of their personal space and comfort level.\n*   **Teasing & Playful Banter:**  Lighthearted teasing can be a fun way to flirt, but be careful not to be mean or insulting.\n*   **Compliments:** Offer genuine compliments about their personality, skills, or style.  Be specific rather than generic.\n*   **Be Supportive:** Offer help or encouragement when they're facing challenges.\n\n**3. More Direct Actions:**\n\n*   **Initiate Contact:**  Don't always wait for them to reach out. Send a text, message, or email to start a conversation.\n*   **Invite Them Out:** Suggest a casual outing like grabbing coffee, seeing a movie, or attending an event you both might enjoy. Frame it as a friendly hangout at first to gauge their interest.\n*   **Express Your Feelings (Carefully):** If you feel like the timing is right and you've gotten to know them better, you can express your feelings more directly.  You could say something like, \"I've really enjoyed spending time with you lately, and I'm starting to develop feelings for you.\"\n*   **Ask Them Out on a Date:** If you're ready for something more serious, you can explicitly ask them out on a date.  Be clear about your intentions.\n\n**4. Important Considerations:**\n\n*   **Respect Their Boundaries:**  Pay attention to their body language and verbal cues. If they seem uncomfortable or disinterested, back off.\n*   **Be Yourself:** Don't try to be someone you're not to impress them. Authenticity is attractive.\n*   **Communication is Key:** Be open and honest with them about your feelings and intentions.\n*   **Be Prepared for Rejection:**  Not everyone will reciprocate your feelings, and that's okay.  Rejection can be painful, but it doesn't mean you're not worthy of love.\n*   **Don't Pressure Them:** Give them time and space to process their feelings.\n*   **Prioritize Their Well-being:** If pursuing a relationship would negatively impact their life or yours, it might be best to remain friends.\n*   **Consider Their Relationship Status:** If they are in a committed relationship, respect that boundary and don't pursue them.\n\n**Example Scenarios & Phrases:**\n\n*   **Casual Conversation Starter:** \"Hey, how was your weekend?\" or \"I heard you're into [shared interest]. That's awesome!\"\n*   **Inviting Them Out (Friendly):** \"I'm going to check out that new coffee shop on Saturday. Want to come along?\"\n*   **Inviting Them Out (Date):** \"I was wondering if you'd be interested in going out sometime? Maybe dinner on Friday?\"\n*   **Expressing Feelings (Subtle):** \"I always have so much fun when I'm around you.\"\n*   **Expressing Feelings (Direct):** \"I've really enjoyed getting to know you, and I think I'm starting to have feelings for you.  I wanted to be honest about that.\"\n\n**Key Takeaway:**\n\nThe best approach depends on the specific situation, your personality, and the other person's personality.  Be observant, be respectful, and most importantly, be yourself! Good luck!\n",
